  "prompt": "A bag contains 4 balls. Two balls are drawn at random and are found to be white. What is the probability that all balls are white?",
  "response": "Let $B$ be the event that the bag contains 4 balls. Let $W$ be the event that two balls are drawn at random and are found to be white.\nWe want to find the probability that all balls are white, given that two balls drawn are white. Let $A$ be the event that all balls are white.\nWe have the following possibilities for the number of white balls in the bag:\n\\begin{itemize}\n    \\item 0 white balls\n    \\item 1 white ball\n    \\item 2 white balls\n    \\item 3 white balls\n    \\item 4 white balls\n\\end{itemize}\nLet $X$ be the number of white balls in the bag. We are given that $X$ can be any integer from 0 to 4.\nSince we are given that two balls are drawn and found to be white, $X$ must be at least 2. So $X$ can be 2, 3, or 4.\nWe want to find $P(X=4 | \\text{two balls drawn are white})$, which is $P(A|W)$.\nBy Bayes' Theorem,\n$$P(A|W) = \\frac{P(W|A) P(A)}{P(W)}$$\nWe assume that each possibility for $X$ is equally likely, so $P(X=2) = P(X=3) = P(X=4) = \\frac{1}{3}$ given that $X \\ge 2$.\nThen $P(A) = P(X=4) = \\frac{1}{3}$.\n$P(W|A) = P(\\text{two balls are white} | \\text{all balls are white}) = 1$.\n$P(W) = P(W|X=2) P(X=2) + P(W|X=3) P(X=3) + P(W|X=4) P(X=4)$\n$P(W|X=2) = \\frac{\\binom{2}{2}}{\\binom{4}{2}} = \\frac{1}{6}$\n$P(W|X=3) = \\frac{\\binom{3}{2}}{\\binom{4}{2}} = \\frac{3}{6} = \\frac{1}{2}$\n$P(W|X=4) = \\frac{\\binom{4}{2}}{\\binom{4}{2}} = 1$\nSo,\n$$P(W) = \\frac{1}{6} \\cdot \\frac{1}{3} + \\frac{1}{2} \\cdot \\frac{1}{3} + 1 \\cdot \\frac{1}{3} = \\frac{1}{18} + \\frac{1}{6} + \\frac{1}{3} = \\frac{1+3+6}{18} = \\frac{10}{18} = \\frac{5}{9}$$\nThen\n$$P(A|W) = \\frac{P(W|A) P(A)}{P(W)} = \\frac{1 \\cdot \\frac{1}{3}}{\\frac{5}{9}} = \\frac{1/3}{5/9} = \\frac{1}{3} \\cdot \\frac{9}{5} = \\frac{3}{5}$$\n\nThus,\n$$P(A|W) = \\frac{3}{5}$$\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{3/5}$",
